[2] China - Xinjiang province, 7 cases
Date: 20 Sep 2011
Source: USA Today [edited]
http://yourlife.usatoday.com/health/story/2011-09-20/WHO-Polio-strain-spreads-to-China-from-Pakistan/50479722/1


WHO: Polio strain spreads to China from Pakistan
------------------------------------------------
The World Health Organization has warned countries that a 'dangerous'
strain of polio has spread to China from Pakistan.

The U.N. health agency says a genetic link has been confirmed between
wild poliovirus type 1 detected in China and a strain circulating in
Pakistan. It says there have been 7 confirmed cases involving the WPV1
strain detected in China's Xinjiang province, which borders Pakistan,
in the past 2 months.

WHO spokesman Oliver Rosenbauer says type 1 is more dangerous than
type 3 because it is more likely to cause paralysis and spreads more
easily. Type 2 polio has been eradicated [The last wild poliovirus
type 2 isolated was from Aligarh, Western Uttar Pradesh, in October
1999. http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5013a5.htm and
http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5012a2.htm from Apparent
Global Interruption of Wild Poliovirus Type 2 Transmission. MMWR. 30
Mar 2001. 50(12);222-4 - Mod.MPP]

The global health body says countries should strengthen their disease
surveillance systems and travellers to Pakistan should be vaccinated
against polio.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the last ProMED-mail post on this outbreak (Poliomyelitis -
worldwide (12): WHO China, Kenya 20110902.2683) there had been 4
confirmed cases of polio with dates of onset between 3 and 27 Jul
2011. The above report now increases the number of involved cases to
7, suggesting more widespread transmission of the WPV in the affected
area. Noteworthy in this outbreak is that the WPV associated with this
outbreak is genotypically similar to the WPV currently circulating in
Pakistan, one of the 4 remaining polio endemic countries in the
world.

For a map of China showing provinces and demonstrating the shared
border of Xinjiang Autonomous Region with Pakistan, see
http://www.sacu.org/provmap.html. For the interactive
HealthMap/ProMED map of Xinjiang Autonomous Region China, see
http://healthmap.org/r/1g0m. - Mod.MPP]

