[5] Pakistan - Baluchistan
Date: 20 Sep 2011
Source: Daily Times [edited]
http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2011%5C09%5C20%5Cstory_20-9-2011_pg7_26


Polio cases at all-time high in Balochistan
-------------------------------------------
Two more cases of polio were detected in Pishin and Loralai districts
raising the total number of polio cases in Balochistan in this year to
37.

The polio virus had been detected in a 12-month-old [male], resident
of Ghasiabad in Tehsil Dukki of Loralai district, and [another male
child], resident of Union Council Karbala in Pishin. Officials from
the polio control programme and Balochistan Health Department
confirmed both cases. "It was the 9th polio case to be detected in
Pishin district and the majority of the polio cases were from Kila
Abdullah district, where 13 cases have been reported," officials
said.

"After the emergence of fresh cases, the number of children suffering
from polio rose to 37 - a high number as compared to other parts of
Pakistan," UNICEF Immunisation Programme Communication Officer Jawahir
Habib said, adding that at least 89 cases of polio had been reported
so far across the country and that Balochistan was considered to be
the worst-affected. "The virus is spreading fast in the northern areas
of Balochistan," an official of the polio control programme said. "We
can say that the province is in the grip of poliovirus [circulation]
and adequate measures are desperately needed to control this spreading
virus."

Jawahir Habib of UNICEF expressed concern and said that the virus had
spread to previously unaffected Kalat, Kohlu, Khuzdar, Noshki, Loralai
and Dera Bugti. "Around 1.5 million children below the age of 5 in
Balochistan are at risk of polio infection due to the current
outbreak. Balochistan hits number one position with the highest number
of polio cases in the country," she added.

As many as 13 children were infected by the polio virus in Kila
Abdullah, 9 in Pishin, 5 in Quetta, 3 in Khuzdar, 3 in Naushki, one in
Kolhu Kalat, Loralai and Dera Bugti each. Health officials fear that
the figure may rise in coming days and blamed parents who were
reluctant to administer their children polio vaccination.

A 6-day anti-polio drive was kicked off across the province on Monday
[19 Sep 2011] during which children below the age of 5 will be
administered an anti-polio vaccine.

[Byline: Mohammad Zafar]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As mentioned above, Pakistan is one of the 4 remaining polio endemic
countries in the world. Baluchistan (Balochistan) is considered a
resource poor province in the country and can be found on a map at
http://www.nationsonline.org/maps/pakistan_map.jpg. The province
shares borders with Iran and Afghanistan, the latter also being a
polio endemic country. For the HealthMap/ProMED map of Baluchistan
Pakistan, see http://healthmap.org/r/1g0n.

As mentioned in the above newswire, there have been 84 cases of polio
confirmed in Pakistan thus far this year. This represents an increase
in 25 cases in the past 6 weeks (see ProMED-mail post Poliomyelitis -
worldwide (09): India, Pakistan, Nigeria 20110808.2402).

The common theme in the above events is the continued cross border
transmission of the WPV in both Africa and Asia. And more importantly
the continued "silent" transmission of the WPV in these areas. In the
case of the events in East Africa, there was introduction of WPV from
Nigeria into the Sudan in 2004, following which there was known
transmission in 2004 and 2005 (known transmission defined as paralytic
cases were identified associated with the WPV transmission in Sudan.
No cases were identified in 2006, and then cases occurred again in
2007 through to the present. In 2009, there were cases in Kenya and
Uganda genotypically related to the WPV known to be circulating in the
southern Sudan at that time. Another year went by and in 2010 a case
in Uganda appeared, genotypically similar to those seen in Kenya in
2009. Again, another year has gone by and in 2011 there are cases in
Kenya genotypically similar to the WPV identified in the 2010 case in
Uganda.

The paralytic to non-paralytic ratio for WPV infection is considered
to be an average of one paralytic case for every 200 persons infected
with the WPV. The range of this ratio is from a high of one paralytic
case per every 50 persons infected with WPV to a low of one paralytic
case per every 1000 persons infected with WPV. Is the situation in
East Africa related to a WPV that has a one per 1000 paralytic to
non-paralytic ratio where it takes approximately one year to infect
1000 individuals resulting in the one paralytic case that leads to a
heightened vaccination response in the affected area? Or is the
situation that there are paralytic cases that are being missed by the
surveillance efforts. Will the endgame for polio eradication include
the more labor intensive (and costly) need for increased environmental
sampling for WPV in remote areas to detect areas with silent
transmission of the WPV? - Mod.MPP]
